                <note rend="inline" type="source">550.S1/245: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Geneva (<persName corresp="#p_VSRG1" type="to"
                        >Gilbert</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-10-07T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 7, 1932—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>152. <persName corresp="#p_WHR1">Wilson</persName>’s 20, October 5, 5 p.m. The
                    appropriation for participation in an “international monetary conference” was
                    adopted in amendment of the Executive’s recommendation for one for “an
                    international economic conference” after a considerable debate in which several
                    leading Senators favored the substitution as a limitation on the President’s
                    possible action.<note n="20" xml:id="d583fn20">See <hi rend="italic"
                            >Congressional Record</hi>, vol. 75, pt. 13, pp. 14241–14251.</note>
                    “Monetary and Financial Conference” appeared to be definitely adopted at
                    Lausanne, in the Council resolution, and other League and international
                    documents. In all the circumstances the apparent change omitting “monetary” may
                    excite embarrassing congressional criticism.</p>
                <p>Quiet reestablishment of “monetary” at suitable opportunity would appear
                    desirable. In the meantime Department will consider title unsettled.</p>
                <p>Discuss informally with Secretariat.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
